The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | CA rules out ban on sledging
                                                   CRICKET BRIEFS
                      
	CA rules out ban on sledging   
	Melbourne: Cricket Australia (CA) has made it clear that it would not support a total ban on sledging as the existing ICC Code of Conduct was good enough to deal with the issue. Cricket Australias position is that the ICC Code of Conduct already covers this issue, a CA spokesman said. A total ban on sledging had not been supported, he added. The CA official added that even if a total ban is imposed, conflicts related to verbal abuse would be decided only on the basis of the existing code.  
	Tigers win         
	 Calcutta: Kolkata Tigers defeated Chandigarh Lions by 22 runs in a virtual semi-final match of the of the Edelweiss 20s Challenge. Some lovely batting from Abhishek Jhunjhunwala and Rohan Gavaskar helped the Tigers reach 165/7. In reply, the Lions were dismissed for 143 thanks to debutant Nachims 4/27.         
	BRIEF SCORES         
	Kolkata Tigers 165/7 in (Jhunjhunwala 62; Hall 3/37). Chandigarh Lions 143 in 18.2 ovs (A. Nachim 4/27). Kolkata Tigers won by 22runs         
	Lanka request         
	 Colombo: Sri Lanka Cricket (SLC) has requested the Board of Control for Cricket in India (BCCI) to shift the first Test of the three-match series between the two countries in July from Galle to Sinhalese Sports Ground in view of the Saarc summit. According to the earlier schedule, Galle was to host the first Test.               
	Shoaib ready         
	 Karachi: Pakistan bowler Shoaib Akhtar says he is ready to face charges of indiscipline brought against him by the PCB and will appear before the disciplinary committee on April 1.         
	Asif out         
	 Karachi: Pakistans leading fast bowler Mohammad Asif has been ruled out of next months one-day series against Bangladesh.                                                                                                                         
